Kiess's frontier cartography office maintains a detailed record of the Cairn Wars period as an ongoing case study in what route governance without multi-city coordination produces.
The wars are cited as evidence for Kiess's position on frontier route authority: no single city should be able to claim inheritance of route law that predates the Five Cities system.
Kiess's northern routes were not directly affected by the Cairn Wars but were affected by their aftermath: trade route diversion increased Kiess's strategic importance.
The anti-sealed-warrant doctrine applies to the Cairn Wars: the Reach Wardens' authority claim is exactly the type of inherited-but-undisclosed authority claim Kiess's charter prohibits.
Kiess's position: the Cairn Wars produced the Reach's current patchwork because no institution had the authority or the mandate to enforce a settlement.

