Kethari water-memory preserves the most detailed record of the Cairn Wars' hydrological effects on the Saltglass Reach.
Cairn station seizures included control of associated water points; each station captured represented a subsurface water access point in Kethari's aquifer map.
The pattern of seizures is visible in Kethari water-memory as a period of systematic human interference with the Reach's water-access points.
Kethari water-readers track which stations changed hands multiple times during the Cairn Wars by the aquifer chemistry disturbance that each changeover produced.
The Aquifer Covenant's renegotiation after the Cairn Wars is documented in Kethari water-memory as a period of intense human interest in Kethari subsurface knowledge.
Both the surviving Reach Wardens and Mafdet's Harbor Wardens consulted Kethari water-readers during the post-Cairn Wars route authority negotiations.
Kethari position: the Cairn Wars were a human dispute about human institutions. The water did not care who held the gates. The water only tracks who changed the chemistry.

