Serathi sky-readers observed the Cairn Wars from their elevated routes above the Saltglass Reach.
The war's progression across the Reach was visible as a ground-level disruption pattern: caravan movement shifting from the established three-route system to irregular pathways.
Serathi sky-road corridors above the Reach were not directly contested during the Cairn Wars; ground-level route violence did not typically extend to aerial routes.
However, the Serathi roost-chronicles document the Cairn Wars' temporal signature: the period of maximum ground-route irregularity, measured by caravan pattern disruption, lasted approximately three generations.
Serathi in Mafdet provided aerial route assessments during the post-Cairn Wars route authority negotiations: they could confirm which ground-level routes were actively used and which were abandoned.
